      <header>
      <div class="teaser-thumbnail" style="background: #265969"><a href="/deeplinks/2019/04/government-fights-trap-effs-nsa-spying-case-catch-22"><img src="https://www.eff.org/files/styles/teaser/public/banner_library/og-nsa-1.png?itok=AgBAlqyn" width="250" height="250" alt="" /></a></div><div class="node-content-type-byline blog"><a href="/updates?type=blog">Deeplinks Blog</a>
<span class="node-author"> by <a href="/about/staff/cindy-cohn">Cindy Cohn</a>, <a href="/about/staff/karen-gullo">Karen Gullo</a></span>
<span class="node-date"> | April 11, 2019</span>
</div>              <h3 class="node__title"><a href="/deeplinks/2019/04/government-fights-trap-effs-nsa-spying-case-catch-22" rel="bookmark">Government Fights to Trap EFF’s NSA Spying Case in a Catch-22</a></h3>
            
    </header>
  
  
  <div class="node__content">
    <div class="eff-translation-links"></div><div class="field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden"><div class="field__items"><div class="field__item even">The U.S. government admits—and, of course, it’s common knowledge—that the NSA conducts mass, dragnet surveillance of hundreds of millions of Americans’ communications. It has done so via a series of different technical strategies and legal arguments for over 18 years. Yet the Justice Department insists that our legal fight against...</div></div></div>  </div>

